---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Open Purifier | Chouhan Industries | Open Hardware"
  ogTitle="Open Purifier | Chouhan Industries"
  description="A fully open, modular water purifier. Choose your filtration stages, sensors, and power, and see exactly what is in your water and what comes out."
  url="https://chouhan.ai/products/open-purifier.html"
>

  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <p class="eyebrow"><a href="/products.html" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: none;">Products</a> / Open Purifier</p>
      <h1>Open Purifier</h1>
      <p class="page-sub">A fully open, modular water purifier. Choose the filtration stages, the sensors, and the power
        supply. Every cartridge is documented, and the core measures your water going in and coming out, so you can see
        exactly what it removed.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="page-section surface" id="open-purifier">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="about-body">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">The Problem</p>
          <p class="lead">Your filter is a black box, and so is your water.</p>
          <div class="detail">
            <p>Cartridges are proprietary and sealed. Some carry a chip so the unit refuses any filter but the
              manufacturer's own. You cannot inspect the media, substitute it, or refill it, and the day the company
              stops selling the cartridge, the whole appliance is landfill.</p>
            <p>Worse, you never learn what the filter actually did. The sensors, if there are any, report a green light
              and nothing else. You are asked to trust a closed box with the one thing you drink every day.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">The Approach</p>
          <p class="lead">An open filtration stack, measured going in and coming out.</p>
          <div class="detail">
            <p>Open Purifier separates the water from everything around it. Stages are swappable modules on a standard
              housing. Choose sediment, carbon, reverse osmosis, ultrafiltration, and UV in the order your water needs.
              Every membrane and cartridge is documented and refillable, and third-party media drops straight in.</p>
            <p>A common monitoring core sits across the stack and reads the water before and after each stage. It tells
              you your TDS, turbidity, and pH in and out, tracks how much life each filter has left, and serves all of
              it to your network. The green light becomes a number you can check.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <p class="section-label">Architecture</p>
      <h2
        style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 2rem); font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: 48px;">
        Every stage. Your choice.</h2>
      <div class="stack-diagram">
        <div class="stack-layer">
          <div class="stack-info">
            <p class="stack-label">Source Input</p>
            <p class="stack-desc">The water that feeds the stack.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="stack-chips">
            <span class="stack-chip">Tap</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Well</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Rainwater</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Tank</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stack-layer stack-modules">
          <div class="stack-info">
            <p class="stack-label">Filtration Stages</p>
            <p class="stack-desc">Swappable modules, in the order you need.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="stack-chips">
            <span class="stack-chip">Sediment</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Carbon</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">RO Membrane</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Ultrafiltration</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">UV</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Remineralizer</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stack-layer stack-api">
          <div class="stack-info">
            <p class="stack-label">Monitoring Core</p>
            <p class="stack-desc">Reads the water in and out, and serves it back.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="stack-chips">
            <span class="stack-chip">Flow</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">TDS</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Sensors</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Filter Life</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Logging</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">API Server</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stack-layer">
          <div class="stack-info">
            <p class="stack-label">Output</p>
            <p class="stack-desc">Where the clean water goes.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="stack-chips">
            <span class="stack-chip">Drinking Tap</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Storage Tank</span>
            <span class="stack-chip">Dispense</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section surface">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <p class="section-label">Configuration</p>
      <h2
        style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 2rem); font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: 48px;">
        Every part. Your call.</h2>
      <div class="omp-grid">
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Filtration Stages</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>Sediment (5 / 1 micron)</li>
            <li>Activated Carbon</li>
            <li>Reverse Osmosis</li>
            <li>Ultrafiltration</li>
            <li>UV Sterilizer</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Sensing</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>TDS (in and out)</li>
            <li>Turbidity</li>
            <li>pH</li>
            <li>Flow Rate</li>
            <li>Filter Life</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Membrane &amp; Cartridge</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>Standard Housing</li>
            <li>Refillable Cartridge</li>
            <li>Third-Party Media</li>
            <li>Remineralizer</li>
            <li>No DRM</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Dispense</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>Drinking Tap</li>
            <li>Chilled</li>
            <li>Hot</li>
            <li>Sparkling</li>
            <li>Storage Tank</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Monitoring</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>Live Readout</li>
            <li>Timestamped Log</li>
            <li>API Server</li>
            <li>Filter Alerts</li>
            <li>Auto Flush</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="omp-item">
          <p class="omp-title">Enclosure &amp; Power</p>
          <ul class="module-list">
            <li>Countertop</li>
            <li>Under-Sink</li>
            <li>Wall-Mount</li>
            <li>Stainless / Glass</li>
            <li>Standard AC</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="about-body">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Software</p>
          <p class="lead">You don't trust the light. You read the water.</p>
          <div class="detail">
            <p>The stages, power, and form are chosen when you order the hardware. The SDK is for the running unit:
              connect to any Open Purifier on your network and read the water quality straight from the core, in and
              out. Python, Rust, and C.</p>
            <p>Ask what each filter has left, trigger a flush, and log every reading over time. The number on the wall
              and the number on your network come from the same sensors.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="code-block">
            <div class="code-header">
              <span class="code-lang">Python</span>
              <div class="code-dots"><span></span><span></span><span></span></div>
            </div>
            <pre><span class="kw">import</span> <span class="c">openpurifier</span>

<span class="comment"># connect to a purifier on your network</span>
<span class="c">unit</span> = <span class="c">openpurifier</span>.<span class="fn">connect</span>(<span class="s">"purifier.local"</span>)

<span class="comment"># read the water going in and coming out</span>
<span class="c">water</span> = <span class="c">unit</span>.<span class="fn">quality</span>()
<span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="c">water</span>.<span class="c">tds_in</span>, <span class="c">water</span>.<span class="c">tds_out</span>)  <span class="comment"># 412, 18 ppm</span>
<span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="c">water</span>.<span class="c">ph</span>, <span class="c">water</span>.<span class="c">turbidity</span>)     <span class="comment"># 7.2, 0.1 NTU</span>

<span class="comment"># how much life is left in each stage?</span>
<span class="kw">for</span> <span class="c">stage</span> <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="c">unit</span>.<span class="fn">filters</span>():
    <span class="fn">print</span>(<span class="c">stage</span>.<span class="c">name</span>, <span class="c">stage</span>.<span class="c">life</span>)  <span class="comment"># "carbon", 0.63</span>

<span class="comment"># flush the membrane on demand</span>
<span class="c">unit</span>.<span class="fn">flush</span>()</pre>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <p class="section-label">Roadmap</p>
      <h2
        style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 2rem); font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: 48px;">
        One purifier. Built in stages.</h2>
      <div class="roadmap-grid">
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 1</p>
          <h3>Core &amp; Basic Filtration</h3>
          <p>The monitoring core with a sediment and carbon stack on a standard housing. The first open cartridge you can
            open, inspect, and refill.</p>
          <span class="status">In Development</span>
        </div>
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 2</p>
          <h3>Water Monitoring</h3>
          <p>TDS, turbidity, and pH sensors read the water in and out. A live readout and a timestamped log, on the unit
            and served to your network.</p>
          <span class="status">Planned</span>
        </div>
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 3</p>
          <h3>Membrane &amp; Advanced Stages</h3>
          <p>Reverse osmosis, ultrafiltration, and UV modules. The core learns to flush the membrane and track its life
            across every stage.</p>
          <span class="status">Planned</span>
        </div>
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 4</p>
          <h3>Open Cartridge Standard</h3>
          <p>Publish the housing and cartridge specification. Refillable bodies, third-party media, and remineralizers
            drop into any Open Purifier without a chip to defeat.</p>
          <span class="status">Planned</span>
        </div>
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 5</p>
          <h3>Form Factors</h3>
          <p>Under-sink, wall-mount, and countertop bodies in stainless and glass, all running on standard AC. The same
            core, sized for a kitchen or a building.</p>
          <span class="status">Research</span>
        </div>
        <div class="roadmap-item">
          <p class="roadmap-phase">Phase 6</p>
          <h3>Open Purifier Standard</h3>
          <p>Publish the full connector and housing specification so any stage, sensor, or supply can be built by anyone.
            The purifier becomes a standard.</p>
          <span class="status">Research</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-section surface">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align: center; max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <p class="section-label">Get Involved</p>
      <h2
        style="font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 2rem); font-weight: 300; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        The stack is open. The water is yours to see.</h2>
      <p style="font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: 300; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 40px;">We
        are in active design. Follow the build log, contribute to the specification, or propose a filtration stage,
        sensor, or cartridge.</p>
      <div style="display: flex; gap: 16px; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap;">
        <a href="/open-source.html" class="btn-primary">View Repository</a>
        <a href="/blog.html" class="btn-secondary">Build Log</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
